./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-custody-and-receiving-surface-255ec907071592a1.md:30:Structural observation: Tannisho strongly supports vow-held custody: Amida's vow carries salvific efficacy and self-power calculation is treated as deviation. Yet it still requires hearing, entrusting, teacher lineage, and restricted readiness, so a receiving surface remains visible. SN 22.59 negates ownership and mastery over the aggregates, but the discourse still depends on instruction, discernment, memory, and seeing with right understanding, so causal-process custody does not eliminate local investigation. Brihadaranyaka 3.7.23 gives the opposite residue policy: ordinary objectification fails, but the hidden knower or inner controller is authorized as the remainder. Dogen's practice-realization strains the model because practice and realization are not cleanly separable stages, making custody and receiving surface look like an analyst-imposed split. These primary texts support the distinction as a useful coding question, but not as a proven independent structure.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-custody-and-receiving-surface-255ec907071592a1.md:32:Secondary literature gap: This audit used accessible translations and open academic or practitioner-facing sources. It did not fully close-read Shinran's Kyogyoshinsho, Dogen scholarship, Dzogchen or Mahamudra manuals, John of the Cross, Teresa of Avila, Christian grace controversy sources, or Sanskrit, Pali, Japanese, Tibetan, and Latin originals. It also did not run practitioner interviews. Novelty should not rise without split-source coding and interview evidence.
