./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-entry-state-ledger-4299246a4ab81e4e.md:68:Why it strains the model: If a path is entered by gradual socialization, inherited belonging, or a practice-realization grammar that refuses a boundary between practice and realization, then no discrete entry-state capacity may be identifiable. The ledger may become a total life-history description rather than a threshold model. It also becomes hard to distinguish grammar from institution, family, habit, and ordinary enculturation.
./reviews/originality/2026-05-26-the-entry-state-ledger-4299246a4ab81e4e.md:76:- If: Capacity locus and grammar are separable. Then: Within one tradition, sublineages or debates that share institution and culture but differ on grace, effort, vow, sudden awakening, or teacher-mediated recognition will show different threshold safeguards and different named entry failures. Weakens if: If intra-tradition differences do not change safeguards once institution and social setting are held constant, grammar may be secondary rhetoric. Test surface: Augustinian versus Pelagian disputes, jiriki versus tariki debates, gradual versus sudden Chan, or Soto practice-realization versus koan-curriculum entry.
