./runs/20260525-214515-codex-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:11:After de-identification, traditions face a practical question: if the ordinary self is no longer trusted as owner, what holds action, care, and meaning together? The answer is a custody policy. Advaita gives custody to unobjectifiable knowing, early Buddhism refuses custody and lets dependent functioning remain ownerless, Zhuangzi gives custody to empty responsiveness, Dogen gives it to the complete present act, Ibn Arabi gives it to divine self-disclosure, and Plotinus gives it to return toward the One. This variable may explain why similar self-emptying practices yield different ethics and metaphysics without treating their resemblance as proof of one hidden reality.
./runs/20260525-214515-codex-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/output.md:24:- Additional source cards: Dogen's Uji, Zhuangzi Inner Chapters, Ibn Arabi's Fusus al-Hikam, Plotinus Enneads, and Friston FEP for empirical-adjacent boundary language.
./runs/20260526-140006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:15:This pattern holds across six traditions. Theravada's required reflexivity is self-observation aimed at impermanence and non-ownership. Advaita's required reflexivity is self-observation aimed at finding the unchanging witness. Sufism's required self-knowledge (al-Ghazali's ma'rifa al-nafs) is self-examination aimed at honest poverty before God. Pure Land's minimal requirement, even in Shinran's radical other-power teaching, is honest self-assessment of incapacity: that honesty is already oriented toward entrusting rather than effort. Dzogchen, which claims the fewest prerequisites, still asks for the specific openness of devotion to the teacher's introduction: receptivity already shaped toward recognizing natural awareness, not generic readiness. Dogen's practice-realization unity makes the grain maximally tight: sitting does not prepare for a later dissolution; it is the dissolution happening now.
./runs/20260526-140006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:41:- Dogen, Bendowa: 'To suppose that practice and realization are not one is a non-Buddhist view.' Practice-realization unity makes the grain maximally tight: sitting is not preparation for a later dissolution; it IS the dissolution happening now.
./runs/20260526-143005-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:21:Activity-centered credit refuses the separation between doing and result. Dogen's shusho-itto (practice-realization as one) insists that sitting is already the activity of enlightenment, not a method aimed at a future state. The question 'who produces enlightenment?' dissolves because production and realization are one.
./runs/20260526-143005-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:29:Each tradition's safeguards are calibrated to its own attribution pattern. Buddhism pairs practitioner-centered effort with not-self teaching, so the very capacity required for the path is what the path eventually dissolves. Pure Land pairs source-centered credit with the nembutsu and community as anchors against antinomian drift. The Bhagavad Gita pairs split credit with the insistence on svadharma (prescribed duty), so that detachment from results does not become detachment from responsibility. Soto Zen pairs activity-centered credit with precepts, teacher relationship, and communal sitting, so that practice-realization does not become a slogan. Advaita pairs ground-centered credit with preparatory disciplines (sadhana chatushtaya) that the teaching technically renders unnecessary, precisely because premature ground claims are the tradition's characteristic danger.
./runs/20260526-143005-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:54:- Dogen, Bendowa, on shusho-itto (practice-realization as one): 'The view that practice and enlightenment are not one is a non-Buddhist view. In the Buddha-dharma they are one.' Dissolves the question of who produces enlightenment by refusing the separation between practice as cause and result as effect. See Carl Bielefeldt, Dogen's Manuals of Zen Meditation (UC Press, 1990).
./runs/20260526-143005-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:105:- Build a credit-distribution rubric with six fields: (a) credited agent at each stage of practice, (b) behavioral instruction, (c) inner orientation toward effort, (d) predicted failure mode, (e) observed safeguard, (f) tradition's own name for the distribution (jiriki, tariki, prapatti, tawakkul, shusho-itto, etc.). Code at least one primary manual from each of the five types before using the typology in cross-tradition claims.
./runs/20260526-100006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:13:This is not uniform. There is a gradient. At one end, spiritual teaching presents knowledge as transmissible doctrine: one can state the Four Noble Truths, learn the five sheaths, memorize the stations of the path. At the other end, several traditions explicitly identify knowledge and transformation as a single indivisible event. Shankara treats self-knowledge not as information about the Self but as the event in which ignorance falls away; the knowledge just is the liberation, and nothing remains to communicate once the ignorance is gone. His technical term, praptasya praptih, means 'the attainment of what was already attained': there is no new content, only the dissolution of a mistake. Dogen denies that practice produces realization as a separate result; sitting is already the activity of enlightenment expressing itself, not a method aimed at a future cognitive state. Plotinus describes union with the One as the collapse of subject and object into bare identity: 'there is no two,' and the language of seeing and knowing gives way. Al-Ghazali's highest category of knowing, dhawq (tasting), is defined by its untransmissibility: you cannot taste honey by hearing about sweetness.
./runs/20260526-100006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:15:The gradient runs roughly like this. First, transmissible doctrine: knowledge can be stated, debated, and memorized. Second, experiential knowledge with reportable structure: the practitioner can describe stages, qualities, and landmarks, but the description does not replace the having. The Theravada insight stages and the Sufi stations of the path sit here. Third, experiential knowledge with vanishing reportability: the practitioner gestures toward the experience but acknowledges the gesture is inadequate. Wisdom born of meditation and Al-Ghazali's tasting occupy this range. Fourth, transformation-identical knowing: the insight has no residue that survives separation from the transformed knower. Shankara's direct self-knowledge, Dogen's practice-realization, and Plotinus's union belong here.
./runs/20260526-100006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:19:One further consequence: traditions at the transformation-identical end will predictably look thinner, vaguer, and less defensible when studied through propositional analysis, because the analysis strips away the mode in which their knowing lives. A Buddhist trained in stage maps might read 'I am Brahman' and find the content suspiciously bare. An Advaitin might read 'practice is realization' and find the claim frustratingly circular. Both critiques may be artifacts of treating transformation-identical knowing as if it had propositional content waiting to be unpacked.
./runs/20260526-100006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:31:- Thinking method source: Dogen's shusho-itto (practice-realization as one) from Bendowa: 'The view that practice and enlightenment are not one is a non-Buddhist view. In the Buddha-dharma they are one. Inasmuch as practice is based on enlightenment, the practice of a beginner is entirely that of original enlightenment.' I used this as a cognitive lens by treating the act of comparison itself as a practice and asking what that practice realizes. The lens made visible an assumption I had been carrying: that insight always has a separable content that can be placed beside another tradition's content. Dogen denies exactly this separation for Zen realization.
./runs/20260526-100006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:32:- Contrasting method source: the Buddhist three-fold prajna from DN 33 (Sangiti Sutta) and Buddhaghosa's Visuddhimagga: suta-maya-panna (wisdom from hearing), cinta-maya-panna (wisdom from reflection), bhavana-maya-panna (wisdom from meditation). This checked the Dogen lens by showing that Buddhism itself explicitly grades knowledge and holds that only the highest grade is truly transformative. The lower grades have real propositional content. This prevents the Dogen lens from flattening all knowledge into transformation-identity.
./runs/20260526-100006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:41:- Carl Bielefeldt, Dogen's Manuals of Zen Meditation (University of California Press, 1990): scholarly treatment of how shusho-itto resolves the hongaku paradox (if all beings are already enlightened, why practice?).
./runs/20260526-100006-claude-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:83:- Test whether the gradient predicts translation strain: do comparisons between two transformation-identical traditions (Advaita recognition and Zen practice-realization) produce more or less strain than comparisons between a transformation-identical and a stage-graded tradition (Zen and Theravada)?
./runs/20260526-103002-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:23:- Dogen's oneness of practice-verification, summarized at https://www.encyclopediaofbuddhism.org/wiki/Dogen, for the claim that realization is not something to expect outside practice.
./runs/20260525-230454-claude-generate-a-new-original-cross-tradition-finding-/prompt.md:182:After de-identification, traditions face a practical question: if the ordinary self is no longer trusted as owner, what holds action, care, and meaning together? The answer is a custody policy. Advaita gives custody to unobjectifiable knowing, early Buddhism refuses custody and lets dependent functioning remain ownerless, Zhuangzi gives custody to empty responsiveness, Dogen gives it to the complete present act, Ibn Arabi gives it to divine self-disclosure, and Plotinus gives it to return toward the One. This variable may explain why similar self-emptying practices yield different ethics and metaphysics without treating their resemblance as proof of one hidden reality.
