./runs/20260526-140006-codex-generate-original-cross-tradition-observations-c/output.md:15:The familiar near-neighbor is Engler's claim that a person needs enough ego strength for self-observation and affect tolerance before no-self practice. The exact difference is that this model does not ask whether a healthy self is required in general. It splits the requirement into five capacities and tracks where each capacity is placed across stages of the path. Pudgalavada debates, Collins on selfless persons, Buddhist functional-self accounts, and contemporary self-pattern theory already make the Buddhist continuity problem hard to ignore. The exact difference is cross-tradition and architectural: the model predicts that effortful, other-power, direct-introduction, and practice-realization traditions will distribute receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration differently. The closest new pressure comes from Pure Land and Dzogchen. Instead of treating them as anomalies that need no self-capacity, the model predicts that they compress the capacity load into hearing, entrusting, recognition, teacher relation, and post-recognition stabilization. That graded relocation is the potentially original contribution, while the basic insight that self-dissolving practice needs functional capacities is strongly precedented.
